1
00:00:09,661 --> 00:00:12,969
- I have dedicated my life,

2
00:00:13,013 --> 00:00:18,322
my entire life,
since being a boy to now,

3
00:00:18,366 --> 00:00:20,585
to being an artist,

4
00:00:20,629 --> 00:00:26,983
and to do so in a way that was,
to me, self-righteous.

5
00:00:27,027 --> 00:00:30,073
I want the world to be
the way that I envision it.

6
00:00:30,117 --> 00:00:36,340
And that means that the world
is full of conflicts,

7
00:00:36,384 --> 00:00:38,429
and so am I.

8
00:00:38,473 --> 00:00:41,998
I'm in conflict with everything
out there that pisses me off,

9
00:00:42,042 --> 00:00:46,872
that upsets me,
that's, you know, not--

10
00:00:46,916 --> 00:00:50,485
that's not just,
that's not right.

11
00:00:50,528 --> 00:00:53,357
- A speedy trial
in front of a jury of peers,

12
00:00:53,401 --> 00:00:55,925
it's one of our
Constitutional rights.

13
00:00:55,968 --> 00:00:58,232
But there are those
that think the Sixth Amendment

14
00:00:58,275 --> 00:01:02,323
ought to be amended
to include trial by mainframe.

15
00:01:02,366 --> 00:01:05,761
- When jurors found OJ Simpson
not guilty,

16
00:01:05,804 --> 00:01:08,720
more than a difference
of opinion separated them

17
00:01:08,764 --> 00:01:11,897
from New York computer
scientist Joseph Bonuso.

18
00:01:11,941 --> 00:01:14,639
- We found OJ guilty
beyond a reasonable doubt.

19
00:01:14,683 --> 00:01:16,293
He was guilty of murder.

20
00:01:16,337 --> 00:01:18,078
- As designed,
the Solomon Project

21
00:01:18,121 --> 00:01:20,036
at the New York University
Law School

22
00:01:20,080 --> 00:01:22,865
is supposed to take the jury
out of jurisprudence,

23
00:01:22,908 --> 00:01:25,389
casting all trials
to the impartiality

24
00:01:25,433 --> 00:01:27,174
of artificial intelligence.

25
00:01:27,217 --> 00:01:29,176
Testimony, evidence,
and precedence

26
00:01:29,219 --> 00:01:31,091
were entered into the computer,

27
00:01:31,134 --> 00:01:34,137
and a complicated formula
using fuzzy logic

28
00:01:34,181 --> 00:01:35,834
helped render a verdict.

29
00:01:35,878 --> 00:01:37,532
[tape rewinding]

30
00:01:37,575 --> 00:01:41,057
- A jury is a manipulated group
of puppets.

31
00:01:41,101 --> 00:01:44,060
[playful music]

32
00:01:44,104 --> 00:01:47,759
♪

33
00:01:47,803 --> 00:01:50,806
- As a prankster, I always
have my guard up in general,

34
00:01:50,849 --> 00:01:52,634
especially
when I hear Joey's name.

35
00:01:52,677 --> 00:01:54,375
- You run...
- A brothel for dogs.

36
00:01:54,418 --> 00:01:56,028
- A brothel for dogs.

37
00:01:56,072 --> 00:01:57,682
- How would you feel

38
00:01:57,726 --> 00:01:59,728
if you had covered
Joey Skaggs' Cathouse for Dogs?

39
00:01:59,771 --> 00:02:01,251
- Would you welcome the inventor

40
00:02:01,295 --> 00:02:03,862
of the fish tank condo,
Joey Skaggs.

41
00:02:03,906 --> 00:02:07,170
- Joey Skaggs, he's fooled
every major American network

42
00:02:07,214 --> 00:02:08,911
with his elaborate hoaxes.

43
00:02:08,954 --> 00:02:10,956
- Print this guy, Mike.

44
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:12,567
I want to make sure we never see
him again under any other name.

45
00:02:12,610 --> 00:02:14,308
- How do we even know
that you are Joey Skaggs?

46
00:02:14,351 --> 00:02:15,700
How do we even know
what you're saying

47
00:02:15,744 --> 00:02:17,659
about these media outlets
is true?

48
00:02:17,702 --> 00:02:20,227
- Any journalist who falls
for a Joey Skaggs prank is...

49
00:02:20,270 --> 00:02:22,185
it's their own fault.

50
00:02:22,229 --> 00:02:24,970
- He thinks that cockroaches
are very important to all of us.

51
00:02:25,014 --> 00:02:28,322
- A cockroach hormone pill
to cure everything.

52
00:02:28,365 --> 00:02:29,845
- Cockroach Cure.

53
00:02:29,888 --> 00:02:31,629
Now, would you read
that article?

54
00:02:31,673 --> 00:02:33,936
- It's because
they didn't look closely.

55
00:02:33,979 --> 00:02:35,677
They didn't fact-check.

56
00:02:35,720 --> 00:02:37,505
They didn't make that call
to verify something.

57
00:02:37,548 --> 00:02:39,333
- My parents were missionaries
in Kenya.

58
00:02:39,376 --> 00:02:42,292
[all roaring]

59
00:02:42,336 --> 00:02:44,251
- Would you ever believe
all the things

60
00:02:44,294 --> 00:02:45,904
you see on television?

61
00:02:45,948 --> 00:02:48,385
Hoaxes performed
before your very eyes.

62
00:02:48,429 --> 00:02:49,821
- Don't you feel bad
when you do it?

63
00:02:49,865 --> 00:02:51,606
- I feel very good.

64
00:02:51,649 --> 00:02:54,435
- I was pissed off at Joey
for a period of time.

65
00:02:54,478 --> 00:02:55,958
But I decided to forgive him,

66
00:02:56,001 --> 00:02:58,221
because Joey does
what I really love,

67
00:02:58,265 --> 00:03:00,049
and that is, he makes you laugh,

68
00:03:00,092 --> 00:03:01,877
and when he makes you laugh,
he makes you think.

69
00:03:01,920 --> 00:03:03,922
- Well, about a month ago
we told you about a man

70
00:03:03,966 --> 00:03:05,663
who came up with a way
to render verdicts

71
00:03:05,707 --> 00:03:08,188
without all the arguing
in the jury room.

72
00:03:08,231 --> 00:03:11,321
But he didn't say anything
about being embarrassed,

73
00:03:11,365 --> 00:03:13,584
which is what CNN is right now.

74
00:03:13,628 --> 00:03:16,805
- We've learned his invention
was all a big hoax,

75
00:03:16,848 --> 00:03:18,241
and we fell for it.

76
00:03:18,285 --> 00:03:20,287
- Wow, that thing on TV news

77
00:03:20,330 --> 00:03:22,593
that we were all talking about
wasn't true.

78
00:03:22,637 --> 00:03:24,160
- I remember
being kind of scared.

79
00:03:24,204 --> 00:03:25,901
Like, oh, my God,
we've been found out.

80
00:03:25,944 --> 00:03:27,772
And Joey's like,
"No, this is all part of it.

81
00:03:27,816 --> 00:03:29,992
"It's all part of it,
because they have to find out.

82
00:03:30,035 --> 00:03:31,428
That's the other part."

83
00:03:42,526 --> 00:03:45,573
- I can't put that
on the back of a tricycle.

84
00:03:45,616 --> 00:03:48,010
There's just no way.

85
00:03:48,053 --> 00:03:52,057
So I'm gonna stick
with the missile.

86
00:03:52,101 --> 00:03:54,059
The missile it is.

87
00:04:19,824 --> 00:04:23,611
First, I'd get it extended.

88
00:04:23,654 --> 00:04:27,789
Making sure
that it was supported.

89
00:04:27,832 --> 00:04:30,008
And then I would,
like you said,

90
00:04:30,052 --> 00:04:32,315
a pipe with a flange.

91
00:04:32,359 --> 00:04:35,405
[tool grinding]

92
00:04:40,671 --> 00:04:45,067
We have Iran, you know,
still playing games.

93
00:04:45,110 --> 00:04:48,026
North Korea
still playing games.

94
00:04:48,070 --> 00:04:50,594
You have surveillance drones.

95
00:04:50,638 --> 00:04:54,163
You have Russia being very upset
with what's going on with NATO,

96
00:04:54,206 --> 00:04:57,601
with moving missiles
to their borders.

97
00:04:57,645 --> 00:05:00,387
There are just so many issues
that this relates to, and it's--

98
00:05:00,430 --> 00:05:02,563
- You know what, though?
- And it's satire.

99
00:05:02,606 --> 00:05:04,173
I mean, it's a mobile
rocket launcher.

100
00:05:04,216 --> 00:05:06,306
- The thing is, you know,
something may just,

101
00:05:06,349 --> 00:05:08,612
in the next six weeks, happen.

102
00:05:08,656 --> 00:05:10,092
- Yeah.

103
00:05:10,135 --> 00:05:11,615
- And, it's just gonna need
to be ready.

104
00:05:18,448 --> 00:05:19,971
- What color do we paint it?

105
00:05:20,015 --> 00:05:21,538
We have the North Korean flag
on it,

106
00:05:21,582 --> 00:05:23,627
the Iranian flag on it?

107
00:05:23,671 --> 00:05:27,065
If I had a robe,
I can be an Arab.

108
00:05:32,636 --> 00:05:34,246
I like to mix it up.

109
00:05:34,290 --> 00:05:36,074
It doesn't have
to always be a hoax.

110
00:05:36,118 --> 00:05:39,600
It can be a direct
theatrical piece

111
00:05:39,643 --> 00:05:43,995
which is a political statement
or a confrontation.

112
00:05:44,039 --> 00:05:45,606
I just love the fact

113
00:05:45,649 --> 00:05:49,740
that here I am in the middle
of rural America

114
00:05:49,784 --> 00:05:53,570
with people who,
you know, you wonder

115
00:05:53,614 --> 00:05:58,880
whether they would agree with
your political stance or not,

116
00:05:58,923 --> 00:06:01,404
but they're willing to do it.

117
00:06:01,448 --> 00:06:04,059
The rocket's the rocket.

118
00:06:04,102 --> 00:06:07,192
That'll be a great visual,

119
00:06:07,236 --> 00:06:10,326
peddling down the streets
of New York.

120
00:06:10,370 --> 00:06:12,502
Or wherever.

121
00:06:20,771 --> 00:06:22,860
Jon.

122
00:06:22,904 --> 00:06:24,819
Well, you're not
gonna believe this.

123
00:06:24,862 --> 00:06:30,390
I just came back with Judy
from seeing Sacha Baron Cohen,

124
00:06:30,433 --> 00:06:32,957
Cohen's film, "The Dictator."

125
00:06:33,001 --> 00:06:36,700
And, yeah, so he's got a missile
in it, you know?

126
00:06:36,744 --> 00:06:40,008
And he's paying homage
to North Korea,

127
00:06:40,051 --> 00:06:44,795
and, you know, he's an Arab
building a missile, you know.

128
00:06:44,839 --> 00:06:46,406
[laughing]

129
00:06:46,449 --> 00:06:48,451
It's like, oh, fuck, man.

130
00:06:48,495 --> 00:06:50,235
You know?

131
00:06:50,279 --> 00:06:52,499
But he didn't have it
on the back of a tricycle.

132
00:06:52,542 --> 00:06:54,588
So we'll stick with the rocket.

133
00:06:54,631 --> 00:06:57,895
And we'll just have the mobile
rocket launcher, and that's it.

134
00:06:57,939 --> 00:06:59,549
And I just have to...

135
00:06:59,593 --> 00:07:01,464
I may not dress up
like an Arab,

136
00:07:01,508 --> 00:07:03,161
as I thought I might.

137
00:07:03,205 --> 00:07:05,947
Or as a North Korean,
as I thought I might.

138
00:07:05,990 --> 00:07:07,731
Maybe I should go as Uncle Sam.

139
00:07:07,775 --> 00:07:09,690
I don't know, I don't know.

140
00:07:16,218 --> 00:07:19,656
It's not the same thing, but...

141
00:07:19,700 --> 00:07:24,139
you know,
he's got it covered kind of.

142
00:07:25,532 --> 00:07:27,185
Rethink this one.

143
00:07:29,753 --> 00:07:32,713
You got to be first.

144
00:07:32,756 --> 00:07:35,280
Not always easy.

145
00:07:53,385 --> 00:07:56,650
Look, life throws you
a lot of curveballs.

146
00:07:56,693 --> 00:07:57,912
You have to be prepared for it.

147
00:07:57,955 --> 00:08:00,741
You have to go with the flow.

148
00:08:00,784 --> 00:08:03,526
There's, you know--you don't
have a lot of choices.

149
00:08:03,570 --> 00:08:06,181
And what happened with me was,
my father had dementia.

150
00:08:06,224 --> 00:08:07,922
He was bedridden
for nine years.

151
00:08:07,965 --> 00:08:09,750
My mother was incapable
of living alone

152
00:08:09,793 --> 00:08:11,578
and taking care of herself.

153
00:08:11,621 --> 00:08:13,275
I said that, you know,
when she needed me,

154
00:08:13,318 --> 00:08:14,929
I would be here full-time.

155
00:08:14,972 --> 00:08:17,105
And she needed me.

156
00:08:17,148 --> 00:08:21,979
So I had to give up Hawaii
and New York.

157
00:08:24,765 --> 00:08:29,770
- Right after my husband died,
he came from Hawaii,

158
00:08:29,813 --> 00:08:31,772
and it was a big change for him.

159
00:08:31,815 --> 00:08:36,254
And I'm not gonna say
what he calls this place,

160
00:08:36,298 --> 00:08:40,389
but it's not been
his greatest move,

161
00:08:40,432 --> 00:08:43,958
because he doesn't have access

162
00:08:44,001 --> 00:08:47,570
to the things
that he's used to.

163
00:08:47,614 --> 00:08:50,051
- It's a tricycle,
it's a three-wheeler.

164
00:08:50,094 --> 00:08:52,053
And on the back
of the three-wheeler,

165
00:08:52,096 --> 00:08:58,233
there's a platform that's gonna
hold the confessional booth.

166
00:09:00,627 --> 00:09:02,542
Whoa.

167
00:09:02,585 --> 00:09:04,239
[laughing]

168
00:09:04,282 --> 00:09:05,675
[staples popping]

169
00:09:07,982 --> 00:09:09,549
I've got some crucifixes.

170
00:09:21,430 --> 00:09:23,084
[dramatic music]

171
00:09:23,127 --> 00:09:26,087
- From FOX 5,
this is Election '92.

172
00:09:26,130 --> 00:09:28,437
Good evening, I'm Jack Cafferty
at Madison Square Garden.

173
00:09:28,480 --> 00:09:30,613
Cora Ann will join us shortly
from the studio.

174
00:09:30,657 --> 00:09:32,659
Now, if anyone at
the convention's feeling guilty

175
00:09:32,702 --> 00:09:34,399
about something
they may have done,

176
00:09:34,443 --> 00:09:36,619
they don't have to go far
to confess their sins.

177
00:09:36,663 --> 00:09:38,839
A man who calls himself
Father William

178
00:09:38,882 --> 00:09:40,623
has mounted a portable
confessional booth

179
00:09:40,667 --> 00:09:42,625
on his bicycle.

180
00:09:42,669 --> 00:09:44,714
- For delegates who feel they
may have overindulged a bit,

181
00:09:44,758 --> 00:09:46,629
a Catholic priest has set up

182
00:09:46,673 --> 00:09:49,850
a mobile confessional
outside Madison Square Garden.

183
00:09:49,893 --> 00:09:52,287
- A Southern California priest
has the answer for Catholics

184
00:09:52,330 --> 00:09:54,332
who don't have time to confess.

185
00:09:54,376 --> 00:09:56,378
He calls it Portofess.

186
00:09:56,421 --> 00:09:59,860
- Father Joseph,
who is schlepping a Portofess,

187
00:09:59,903 --> 00:10:03,167
a portable confession booth,
around by bike.

188
00:10:03,211 --> 00:10:06,170
[jaunty music]

189
00:10:06,214 --> 00:10:13,264
♪

190
00:10:16,790 --> 00:10:19,923
- Well, I didn't start out
as a prankster.

191
00:10:19,967 --> 00:10:21,664
I was a child artist.

192
00:10:21,708 --> 00:10:23,492
I had a passion for art.

193
00:10:23,535 --> 00:10:27,452
I always drew,
I painted, I sculpted.

194
00:10:27,496 --> 00:10:30,020
I just knew that I wanted
to be an artist.

195
00:10:30,064 --> 00:10:31,674
That was my dream.

196
00:10:31,718 --> 00:10:35,156
- Most children,
they don't obey their parents.

197
00:10:35,199 --> 00:10:38,115
They don't want to accept
rules and regulations

198
00:10:38,159 --> 00:10:40,161
and come in at a certain time.

199
00:10:40,204 --> 00:10:42,076
He was just a normal child

200
00:10:42,119 --> 00:10:46,297
who just didn't want to do
what Mama and Papa said.

201
00:10:46,341 --> 00:10:49,431
- My parents moved
to a little area

202
00:10:49,474 --> 00:10:53,174
on the Brooklyn-Queens
borderline called Laurel Hill,

203
00:10:53,217 --> 00:10:58,483
by Newtown Creek,
a real industrial slum area.

204
00:10:58,527 --> 00:11:00,703
And there was
Calvary Cemetery there,

205
00:11:00,747 --> 00:11:02,923
the Kosciuszko Bridge.

206
00:11:02,966 --> 00:11:05,926
And off in the distance
was Manhattan.

207
00:11:05,969 --> 00:11:08,929
[dramatic music]

208
00:11:08,972 --> 00:11:12,106
♪

209
00:11:12,149 --> 00:11:13,542
I was a young artist.

210
00:11:13,585 --> 00:11:15,370
I knew what I wanted to be.

211
00:11:15,413 --> 00:11:17,633
And I wanted to be in Manhattan.

212
00:11:17,677 --> 00:11:20,636
[jaunty music]

213
00:11:20,680 --> 00:11:27,687
♪

214
00:11:31,125 --> 00:11:34,302
It was a junior-high-school
art teacher that told me

215
00:11:34,345 --> 00:11:36,260
about the High School
of Art and Design.

216
00:11:36,304 --> 00:11:38,262
And I was really fortunate
enough to be accepted

217
00:11:38,306 --> 00:11:40,525
into this
extraordinary high school.

218
00:11:40,569 --> 00:11:43,615
And it was all young artists,
and the teachers were artists.

219
00:11:43,659 --> 00:11:45,313
And it was inspirational.

220
00:11:45,356 --> 00:11:48,011
- My husband
never agreed, never.

221
00:11:48,055 --> 00:11:49,230
- Well, what does your son do?

222
00:11:49,273 --> 00:11:50,492
He's a fine artist.

223
00:11:50,535 --> 00:11:52,407
What the fuck is a fine artist?

224
00:11:52,450 --> 00:11:54,888
- And I said, well, as far
as I'm concerned, so be it.

225
00:11:54,931 --> 00:11:56,803
It's his life.

226
00:11:56,846 --> 00:11:59,457
And if he says
it's what he wants to do,

227
00:11:59,501 --> 00:12:03,679
that's fine with me.

228
00:12:03,723 --> 00:12:05,986
- You have a dream, a passion.

229
00:12:06,029 --> 00:12:07,901
I'm gonna be an artist.

230
00:12:07,944 --> 00:12:09,772
I'll just do all my work,
and then I'll be discovered.

231
00:12:09,816 --> 00:12:11,992
[laughs]

232
00:12:12,035 --> 00:12:13,776
I'll just paint and paint,
and somebody's gonna go,

233
00:12:13,820 --> 00:12:15,865
"Oh, genius!"

234
00:12:15,909 --> 00:12:19,303
But it doesn't always work out
that way for most people.

235
00:12:19,347 --> 00:12:22,742
You're forced to wait until
you are accepted into a gallery

236
00:12:22,785 --> 00:12:26,571
and then have a show
and then hope for a review.

237
00:12:26,615 --> 00:12:28,225
There was
no immediacy involved.

238
00:12:28,269 --> 00:12:29,531
And I wanted the immediacy.

239
00:12:29,574 --> 00:12:31,272
I like things now.

240
00:12:31,315 --> 00:12:32,839
I said, fuck that.

241
00:12:32,882 --> 00:12:35,189
I'm just--I'm gonna do it
in the streets.

242
00:12:35,232 --> 00:12:36,320
I'm gonna do it my way.

243
00:12:36,364 --> 00:12:39,323
[upbeat rock music]

244
00:12:39,367 --> 00:12:46,417
♪

245
00:12:50,770 --> 00:12:53,207
- Here in the "Time" Magazine
I read about a guy

246
00:12:53,250 --> 00:12:56,601
who took a load of hippies,

247
00:12:56,645 --> 00:12:59,126
who were long-haired,
strange-looking people,

248
00:12:59,169 --> 00:13:01,519
as you well know,

249
00:13:01,563 --> 00:13:03,826
put them on a bus
and took them to Queens.

250
00:13:03,870 --> 00:13:10,877
♪

251
00:13:16,143 --> 00:13:17,840
- We took pictures of people

252
00:13:17,884 --> 00:13:19,842
mowing their lawns
